# The objective - 
- To find the password for LEVEL2 which was stored in an unusual file named - (dashed file)

# The commands you used - 
- ssh udername@hostname -p <port>
- pwd
- ls
- cat ./-    (./ is used to specify that we are looking fir the file the cwd )

# Why your solution worked - 
-  cat - did not work because linux interprets a single hyphen as a flag used to specify some option, so instead we used cat ./ in order to specify the file name as a path so that linux could understand that we want to read the dashed file present in the current working directory.

# Key Linux concepts or commands you learned - 
- how there can be special character / symbols present in the names of files, and can lead to exceptional behaviour.
- the ./ prefix refers to the current working directory and helps distinguish filenames from command options.
- Commands may treat certain characters as special unless the path is specified explicitly.

 